## 4. Module-Level Architecture

### 4.1 File Structure

```
resume_parser/
├── main.py                    # FastAPI application entry point
├── config.py                  # Centralized configuration & skill taxonomy
├── schemas.py                 # Pydantic data models
├── pdf_processor.py           # PDF text extraction
├── entity_extractor.py        # Name, email, phone extraction (spaCy + regex)
├── skills_extractor.py        # Skills extraction (hybrid: exact + semantic)
├── experience_extractor.py    # Work experience extraction (regex patterns)
├── production_monitor.py      # Production metrics & monitoring
├── evaluator.py               # Accuracy evaluation module
├── test_accuracy.py           # Accuracy testing script
├── test_parser.py             # Unit tests
├── requirements.txt           # Python dependencies
├── __init__.py                # Package initialization
├── INFORMATION-TECHNOLOGY/    # Test dataset (120 IT resumes)
├── test_data/                 # Ground truth & review templates
└── logs/                      # Production monitoring logs (JSONL)
```

### 4.2 Module Descriptions

#### [main.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/main.py) — API Server
- **Framework:** FastAPI with Uvicorn ASGI server
- **Endpoints:**

| Endpoint | Method | Description |
|----------|--------|-------------|
| `/` | GET | Health check |
| `/health` | GET | Detailed health check (extractor status) |
| `/parse` | POST | Parse a single resume PDF |
| `/parse-batch` | POST | Parse up to 10 resumes in batch |
| `/metrics` | GET | Get production monitoring metrics |
| `/feedback` | POST | Submit human feedback for accuracy tracking |
| `/accuracy` | GET | Get accuracy from human feedback |

- **Startup behavior:** All ML models (spaCy, Sentence-Transformers, FAISS) are loaded once at server startup to avoid per-request latency
- **File validation:** Max 10MB, PDF only
- **API docs:** Auto-generated at `/docs` (Swagger UI) and `/redoc`

---

#### [pdf_processor.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/pdf_processor.py) — PDF Text Extraction
- **Technology:** pdfplumber
- **Approach:** Page-by-page text extraction with layout analysis
- **Features:**
  - Accepts both file paths and raw bytes (for API uploads)
  - Text cleaning: normalizes whitespace, removes extra newlines
  - Graceful error handling for corrupted PDFs
  - Logs extraction statistics (characters per page)

---

#### [entity_extractor.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/entity_extractor.py) — Contact Information Extraction
- **Technology:** spaCy (en_core_web_trf) + Regex
- **Extraction strategy:**

| Field | Method | Details |
|-------|--------|---------|
| **Name** | spaCy NER | Processes first 1000 characters, looks for `PERSON` entities, validates 2-4 word names |
| **Email** | Regex | Pattern: `[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Z\|a-z]{2,}` |
| **Phone** | Regex | Supports international formats: `+1 555-123-4567`, [(555) 123-4567](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/evaluator.py#327-347), `+91 9876543210` |

- **Model:** `en_core_web_trf` — spaCy's RoBERTa-based transformer model, providing state-of-the-art NER accuracy

---

#### [skills_extractor.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/skills_extractor.py) — Skills Extraction (Hybrid AI Pipeline)
This is the most sophisticated module, using a **4-stage hybrid approach**:

```mermaid
graph LR
    A["Input Text"] --> B["Stage 1:<br/>Exact Matching"]
    B --> C["Stage 2:<br/>Alias Resolution"]
    C --> D["Stage 3:<br/>Fuzzy Matching"]
    D --> E["Stage 4:<br/>Semantic Search"]
    E --> F["Deduplicated<br/>Skills List"]

    style B fill:#4CAF50,color:#fff
    style C fill:#2196F3,color:#fff
    style D fill:#FF9800,color:#fff
    style E fill:#9C27B0,color:#fff
```

| Stage | Method | Technology | What It Catches |
|-------|--------|-----------|-----------------|
| **1. Exact Matching** | Case-insensitive regex with word boundaries | Python [re](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/main.py#105-222) | "Python", "JavaScript", "React" |
| **2. Alias Resolution** | Maps 68 aliases to canonical skill names | Dictionary lookup | "reactjs" → "React", "k8s" → "Kubernetes", "py" → "Python" |
| **3. Fuzzy Matching** | 88% similarity threshold on tokens >4 chars | `difflib.get_close_matches` | "Javscript" → "JavaScript", "Postgresq" → "PostgreSQL" |
| **4. Semantic Search** | FAISS vector similarity on text chunks | Sentence-Transformers + FAISS | "Built machine learning pipelines" → "Machine Learning" |

**Skill Taxonomy:**
- **118 canonical skills** across 9 categories (Languages, Frontend, Backend, Databases, DevOps, Data Science, Tools, Mobile, Other)
- **68 aliases** mapping common acronyms, typos, and variations to canonical names
- **Hierarchical Ontology** with 20+ skill entries containing:
  - `language[]` — inferred programming languages
  - `domain[]` — inferred job domains
  - `parent[]` — parent skill categories
  - `equivalents[]` — industry-equivalent alternatives

**FAISS Index Details:**
- Embedding model: `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` (384-dimensional vectors)
- Index type: `IndexFlatIP` (inner-product for cosine similarity)
- Vectors are L2-normalized before indexing
- Similarity threshold: 0.75 (configurable)
- Text is chunked into up to 100 segments for semantic matching

**Structured Skills Output:**
Beyond the raw skills list, the module produces a rich taxonomy:
```json
{
  "raw_extracted": ["React", "FastAPI"],
  "inferred_languages": ["JavaScript", "TypeScript", "Python"],
  "inferred_domains": ["Web Development", "Frontend", "Backend", "API Development"],
  "inferred_parents": ["Frontend Framework", "Backend Framework"],
  "industry_equivalents": ["Angular", "Vue", "Django", "Flask"],
  "categories": {
    "frontend": ["React"],
    "backend": ["FastAPI"]
  }
}
```

---

#### [experience_extractor.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/experience_extractor.py) — Work Experience Extraction
- **Technology:** Regex pattern matching
- **Approach:**
  1. Find date ranges using patterns like `2020-2022`, `2019 to Present`
  2. Extract 200 characters of context around each date match
  3. Parse company name and job title from preceding lines
  4. Parse role description from following lines
  5. Deduplicate by duration
- **Output:** List of [Experience](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#10-26) objects with company, position, duration, description
- **Additional feature:** Calculates total years of experience from all entries

---

#### [production_monitor.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/production_monitor.py) — Monitoring & Feedback
- **In-memory metrics tracking:**
  - Total requests, success/failure counts
  - Processing time statistics (mean, median)
  - Per-field extraction rates
  - Confidence scores
- **Persistent logging:** JSONL (JSON Lines) daily log files
- **Human feedback loop:** Records human corrections for continuous accuracy measurement
- **Confidence scoring:** Heuristic-based (% of fields successfully extracted)

---

#### [schemas.py](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py) — Data Models
All data models use **Pydantic** for type safety and automatic validation.

| Schema | Purpose | Key Fields |
|--------|---------|------------|
| [Experience](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#10-26) | Single work experience entry | company, position, duration, description |
| [StructuredSkills](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#28-51) | Rich skill taxonomy output | raw_extracted, inferred_languages, inferred_domains, inferred_parents, industry_equivalents, categories |
| [ResumeData](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#53-112) | Complete parsed resume | name, email, phone, skills[], experience[], structured_skills, raw_text |
| [ParseResponse](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#114-138) | API response wrapper | success, data (ResumeData), error, processing_time_ms, timestamp |
| [FieldMetrics](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#140-146) | Accuracy metrics per field | precision, recall, f1_score, accuracy |
| [EvaluationMetrics](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#148-168) | Full evaluation result | per-field metrics + overall_accuracy |
| [GroundTruth](file:///c:/Users/karti/computer_science/praktiki/PythonProject/resume_parser/schemas.py#170-178) | Expected values for testing | filename, name, email, phone, skills[], experience[] |

**Built-in validators:**
- Email validation (must contain `@`)
- Skill deduplication (case-insensitive, preserves first occurrence)

