## 5. AI/ML Pipeline Details

### 5.1 Models Used

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph "Model 1: spaCy en_core_web_trf"
        M1_ARCH["Architecture: RoBERTa Transformer"]
        M1_TASK["Task: Named Entity Recognition (NER)"]
        M1_ENT["Entities: PERSON, ORG, DATE, etc."]
        M1_USE["Used for: Name extraction"]
    end

    subgraph "Model 2: all-MiniLM-L6-v2"
        M2_ARCH["Architecture: MiniLM (6 layers)"]
        M2_TASK["Task: Sentence Embedding"]
        M2_DIM["Output: 384-dim dense vectors"]
        M2_USE["Used for: Semantic skill matching"]
    end

    subgraph "Index: FAISS"
        F_TYPE["Type: IndexFlatIP (Inner Product)"]
        F_SIZE["Size: 118 skill vectors"]
        F_SEARCH["Search: Top-3 per text chunk"]
        F_THRESH["Threshold: 0.75 cosine similarity"]
    end
```

### 5.2 Model Loading & Lifecycle

| Phase | What Happens | Time |
|-------|-------------|------|
| **Startup** | Load spaCy transformer model into GPU/CPU | ~8s |
| **Startup** | Load Sentence-Transformers model | ~4s |
| **Startup** | Encode 118 skills → FAISS index | ~1s |
| **Per-Request** | NER inference on first 1000 chars | ~300ms |
| **Per-Request** | Encode text chunks + FAISS search | ~500ms |
| **Per-Request** | Regex + fuzzy matching | ~50ms |

### 5.3 Why This Architecture?

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| **spaCy en_core_web_trf** over smaller models | Transformer-based NER has significantly better accuracy for name detection across varied resume formats |
| **FAISS** over brute-force similarity | O(1) lookup vs O(n) comparison; scales to thousands of skills; Facebook-backed, battle-tested |
| **Sentence-Transformers** over TF-IDF | Dense vectors capture semantic meaning ("built ML pipelines" → "Machine Learning"), not just keyword overlap |
| **Hybrid 4-stage skills extraction** | Each stage catches different variations: exact → aliases → typos → semantics. Maximizes recall without sacrificing precision |
| **FastAPI** over Flask/Django | Async support, automatic OpenAPI docs, Pydantic integration, highest performance among Python frameworks |
| **pdfplumber** over PyPDF2/PDFMiner | Best balance of accuracy and layout preservation; handles complex PDF layouts better |

